('chunk_ed1fc7b1ed19cb7d8d','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Biome Profile: Tropical Grassland / Savanna','| Feature | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Location** | Between rainforests and hot deserts (~5–15° N/S) — Serengeti (Tanzania/Kenya), Sahel, northern Australia. |
| **Climate & seasonal change** | Hot all year; a distinct **wet season and dry season** — the defining feature. |
| **Soil** | Fairly fertile in places; dry-season fires return nutrients; can bake hard and crack. |
| **Adaptations** | Grasses grow fast in the wet season and lie dormant/deep-rooted in the dry; acacia trees have thorns and small waxy leaves; animals migrate to find water (wildebeest) or store fat. |
| **Threats** | Overgrazing, farming expansion, poaching, desertification, climate change. |
| **Ecological importance** | Supports the world''s largest herds and iconic megafauna; grazing/fire cycle maintains grassland. |
| **Conservation** | National parks (Serengeti NP), anti-poaching, controlled grazing, community conservancies, ecotourism. |

**Analogy:** Savanna grass is like a phone on low-power mode in the dry season — it shuts down above ground and stores energy in the roots until the "recharge" of the rains.
**Misconception:** *"Bushfires in the savanna are always disasters."* Wrong: periodic fire is natural and *necessary* — it recycles nutrients and stops forest taking over. Corrective: the savanna is a fire-adapted biome; suppressing all fire can harm it.
**IB command-term questions:**
1. (Recall) **State** the two seasons of the savanna.
2. (Apply) **Explain** how wildebeest are adapted to seasonal savanna change.
3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Discuss** the role of fire in maintaining the savanna. *(SDG 15.)*','{"biome":2,"profile":1,"tropical":1,"grassland":2,"savanna":7,"feature":2,"detail":1,"location":1,"between":1,"rainforests":1,"and":9,"hot":2,"deserts":1,"serengeti":2,"tanzania":1,"kenya":1,"sahel":1,"northern":1,"australia":1,"climate":2,"seasonal":2,"change":3,"all":2,"year":1,"distinct":1,"wet":2,"season":5,"dry":4,"the":14,"defining":1,"soil":1,"fairly":1,"fertile":1,"places":1,"fires":1,"return":1,"nutrients":2,"can":2,"bake":1,"hard":1,"crack":1,"adaptations":1,"grasses":1,"grow":1,"fast":1,"lie":1,"dormant":1,"deep":1,"rooted":1,"acacia":1,"trees":1,"have":1,"thorns":1,"small":1,"waxy":1,"leaves":1,"animals":1,"migrate":1,"find":1,"water":1,"wildebeest":2,"store":1,"fat":1,"threats":1,"overgrazing":1,"farming":1,"expansion":1,"poaching":2,"desertification":1,"ecological":1,"importance":1,"supports":1,"world":1,"largest":1,"herds":1,"iconic":1,"megafauna":1,"grazing":2,"fire":5,"cycle":1,"maintains":1,"conservation":1,"national":1,"parks":1,"anti":1,"controlled":1,"community":1,"conservancies":1,"ecotourism":1,"analogy":1,"grass":1,"like":1,"phone":1,"low":1,"power":1,"mode":1,"shuts":1,"down":1,"above":1,"ground":1,"stores":1,"energy":1,"roots":1,"until":1,"recharge":1,"rains":1,"misconception":1,"bushfires":1,"are":2,"always":1,"disasters":1,"wrong":1,"periodic":1,"natural":1,"necessary":1,"recycles":1,"stops":1,"forest":1,"taking":1,"over":1,"corrective":1,"adapted":2,"suppressing":1,"harm":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"two":1,"seasons":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"how":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"discuss":1,"role":1,"maintaining":1,"sdg":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_15f4f63a1a0d3a9d8f','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Biome Profile: Temperate Grassland','| Feature | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Location** | Mid-latitude continental interiors — Prairies (North America), Pampas (Argentina), Steppes (Ukraine/Central Asia), Veld (S. Africa). |
| **Climate** | Warm summers, cold winters; moderate rainfall (mostly in summer); no trees over much of the area. |
| **Soil & agriculture** | Deep, dark, very **fertile chernozem** soils rich in humus — among the best farmland on Earth ("breadbaskets"). |
| **Adaptations** | Grasses with deep, dense root mats; grazing animals (bison, pronghorn) with speed and herding; burrowing animals (prairie dogs). |
| **Indigenous lifestyle** | Plains peoples (e.g. **Native American Plains nations**) historically followed bison herds; Mongolian steppe herders are nomadic pastoralists. |
| **Threats** | Ploughing for cereals, overgrazing, soil erosion (Dust Bowl), urban spread. |
| **Economic importance** | Grow the world''s wheat, maize and support cattle ranching — vital to global food supply. |
| **Conservation** | Contour ploughing, crop rotation, shelter belts, protected prairie reserves, no-till farming. |

**Analogy:** Prairie roots form a mat like a woven carpet holding the soil — rip up the carpet (plough badly) and the wind blows the "floor" away, as in the 1930s Dust Bowl.
**Misconception:** *"Grasslands are empty, unused land."* Wrong: they are the planet''s most productive farmland and rich ecosystems. Corrective: "few trees" does not mean "unimportant."
**IB command-term questions:**
1. (Recall) **Name** two temperate grasslands and their continents.
2. (Apply) **Explain** why chernozem soils make grasslands important for agriculture.
3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Analyse** the causes and consequences of the 1930s Dust Bowl. *(SDG 2, 15.)*

---','{"biome":1,"profile":1,"temperate":2,"grassland":1,"feature":1,"detail":1,"location":1,"mid":1,"latitude":1,"continental":1,"interiors":1,"prairies":1,"north":1,"america":1,"pampas":1,"argentina":1,"steppes":1,"ukraine":1,"central":1,"asia":1,"veld":1,"africa":1,"climate":1,"warm":1,"summers":1,"cold":1,"winters":1,"moderate":1,"rainfall":1,"mostly":1,"summer":1,"trees":2,"over":1,"much":1,"the":11,"area":1,"soil":3,"agriculture":2,"deep":2,"dark":1,"very":1,"fertile":1,"chernozem":2,"soils":2,"rich":2,"humus":1,"among":1,"best":1,"farmland":2,"earth":1,"breadbaskets":1,"adaptations":1,"grasses":1,"with":2,"dense":1,"root":1,"mats":1,"grazing":1,"animals":2,"bison":2,"pronghorn":1,"speed":1,"and":6,"herding":1,"burrowing":1,"prairie":3,"dogs":1,"indigenous":1,"lifestyle":1,"plains":2,"peoples":1,"native":1,"american":1,"nations":1,"historically":1,"followed":1,"herds":1,"mongolian":1,"steppe":1,"herders":1,"are":3,"nomadic":1,"pastoralists":1,"threats":1,"ploughing":2,"for":2,"cereals":1,"overgrazing":1,"erosion":1,"dust":3,"bowl":3,"urban":1,"spread":1,"economic":1,"importance":1,"grow":1,"world":1,"wheat":1,"maize":1,"support":1,"cattle":1,"ranching":1,"vital":1,"global":1,"food":1,"supply":1,"conservation":1,"contour":1,"crop":1,"rotation":1,"shelter":1,"belts":1,"protected":1,"reserves":1,"till":1,"farming":1,"analogy":1,"roots":1,"form":1,"mat":1,"like":1,"woven":1,"carpet":2,"holding":1,"rip":1,"plough":1,"badly":1,"wind":1,"blows":1,"floor":1,"away":1,"1930s":2,"misconception":1,"grasslands":3,"empty":1,"unused":1,"land":1,"wrong":1,"they":1,"planet":1,"most":1,"productive":1,"ecosystems":1,"corrective":1,"few":1,"does":1,"not":1,"mean":1,"unimportant":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"name":1,"two":1,"their":1,"continents":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"why":1,"make":1,"important":1,"analyse":2,"evaluate":1,"causes":1,"consequences":1,"sdg":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_27b36907b909141216','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Biome Profile: Hot Desert','| Feature | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Location** | Around 30° N/S under subtropical high pressure — Sahara (Africa), Arabian, Thar (India), Australian outback. |
| **Climate** | Very hot days, cold nights; extreme temperature range; rainfall <250 mm/year, very unreliable. |
| **Soil** | Thin, sandy/stony, low organic matter, often salty; little vegetation to enrich it. |
| **Adaptations** | Plants: cacti store water, spines reduce loss and deter grazers, deep or wide roots, waxy skins. Animals: camels store fat, nocturnal habits, water conservation, light coloured fur. |
| **Indigenous lifestyle** | Nomads such as the **Tuareg (Sahara)** and **Bedouin (Arabia)** travel between water sources, herd camels/goats, use tents and light clothing. |
| **Threats & uniqueness** | Mining, oil extraction, over-abstraction of water, tourism, desertification at edges; unique adaptations found nowhere else. |
| **Conservation** | Protected reserves, sustainable water use, solar-energy projects, controlled grazing, anti-desertification tree planting (e.g. Great Green Wall). |

**Analogy:** A cactus is like a living water bottle with a spiky lid — it hoards every drop and defends it.
**Misconception:** *"Deserts are just lifeless seas of sand."* Wrong: most deserts are rocky, not sandy, and teem with specially adapted life. Corrective: deserts are defined by low rainfall, not by sand or by being lifeless.
**IB command-term questions:**
1. (Recall) **Define** a hot desert by its rainfall.
2. (Apply) **Describe** two adaptations of the camel to desert life.
3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Evaluate** the benefits and drawbacks of large-scale solar projects in deserts. *(SDG 7, 15.)*','{"250":1,"biome":1,"profile":1,"hot":3,"desert":3,"feature":1,"detail":1,"location":1,"around":1,"under":1,"subtropical":1,"high":1,"pressure":1,"sahara":2,"africa":1,"arabian":1,"thar":1,"india":1,"australian":1,"outback":1,"climate":1,"very":2,"days":1,"cold":1,"nights":1,"extreme":1,"temperature":1,"range":1,"rainfall":3,"year":1,"unreliable":1,"soil":1,"thin":1,"sandy":2,"stony":1,"low":2,"organic":1,"matter":1,"often":1,"salty":1,"little":1,"vegetation":1,"enrich":1,"adaptations":3,"plants":1,"cacti":1,"store":2,"water":6,"spines":1,"reduce":1,"loss":1,"and":6,"deter":1,"grazers":1,"deep":1,"wide":1,"roots":1,"waxy":1,"skins":1,"animals":1,"camels":2,"fat":1,"nocturnal":1,"habits":1,"conservation":2,"light":2,"coloured":1,"fur":1,"indigenous":1,"lifestyle":1,"nomads":1,"such":1,"the":3,"tuareg":1,"bedouin":1,"arabia":1,"travel":1,"between":1,"sources":1,"herd":1,"goats":1,"use":2,"tents":1,"clothing":1,"threats":1,"uniqueness":1,"mining":1,"oil":1,"extraction":1,"over":1,"abstraction":1,"tourism":1,"desertification":2,"edges":1,"unique":1,"found":1,"nowhere":1,"else":1,"protected":1,"reserves":1,"sustainable":1,"solar":2,"energy":1,"projects":2,"controlled":1,"grazing":1,"anti":1,"tree":1,"planting":1,"great":1,"green":1,"wall":1,"analogy":1,"cactus":1,"like":1,"living":1,"bottle":1,"with":2,"spiky":1,"lid":1,"hoards":1,"every":1,"drop":1,"defends":1,"misconception":1,"deserts":4,"are":3,"just":1,"lifeless":2,"seas":1,"sand":2,"wrong":1,"most":1,"rocky":1,"not":2,"teem":1,"specially":1,"adapted":1,"life":2,"corrective":1,"defined":1,"being":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"its":1,"apply":1,"describe":1,"two":1,"camel":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":2,"benefits":1,"drawbacks":1,"large":1,"scale":1,"sdg":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_6ad2829e028363979c','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Biome Profile: Tundra','| Feature | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Location** | Far north (Arctic) — northern Alaska, northern Canada, northern Russia; also alpine tundra on high mountains. |
| **Climate** | Freezing for most of the year; short cool summer; very low precipitation ("cold desert"). |
| **Soil & permafrost** | Thin, waterlogged soil over **permafrost** (permanently frozen subsoil) that blocks drainage and root growth. |
| **Adaptations** | Plants: low-growing cushions and mosses, grow fast in short summer, hairy stems. Animals: thick fur/blubber, white winter camouflage, migration (caribou), hibernation. |
| **Vulnerability to climate change** | Warming thaws permafrost, releasing stored methane/CO₂ (a feedback loop); very fragile, slow to recover. |
| **Indigenous lifestyle** | The **Inuit** hunt seals, caribou and fish; historically use skins, sleds and detailed knowledge of ice and seasons. |
| **Threats** | Oil & gas extraction, pipelines, mining, climate warming, pollution. |
| **Conservation** | Protected wilderness, strict extraction limits, cutting global emissions, supporting indigenous stewardship. |

**Analogy:** Permafrost is like a frozen freezer floor beneath a thin thawed rug — water can''t drain through it, so the surface stays soggy and boggy in summer.
**Misconception:** *"Nothing lives in the tundra."* Wrong: it hosts caribou, arctic foxes, migrating birds and hardy plants. Corrective: life is sparse and specialised, not absent.
**IB command-term questions:**
1. (Recall) **Define** "permafrost."
2. (Apply) **Explain** how the Inuit adapt their lifestyle to the tundra.
3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Analyse** why the tundra is especially vulnerable to climate change. *(SDG 13, 15.)*','{"biome":1,"profile":1,"tundra":5,"feature":1,"detail":1,"location":1,"far":1,"north":1,"arctic":2,"northern":3,"alaska":1,"canada":1,"russia":1,"also":1,"alpine":1,"high":1,"mountains":1,"climate":4,"freezing":1,"for":1,"most":1,"the":7,"year":1,"short":2,"cool":1,"summer":3,"very":2,"low":2,"precipitation":1,"cold":1,"desert":1,"soil":2,"permafrost":5,"thin":2,"waterlogged":1,"over":1,"permanently":1,"frozen":2,"subsoil":1,"that":1,"blocks":1,"drainage":1,"and":8,"root":1,"growth":1,"adaptations":1,"plants":2,"growing":1,"cushions":1,"mosses":1,"grow":1,"fast":1,"hairy":1,"stems":1,"animals":1,"thick":1,"fur":1,"blubber":1,"white":1,"winter":1,"camouflage":1,"migration":1,"caribou":3,"hibernation":1,"vulnerability":1,"change":2,"warming":2,"thaws":1,"releasing":1,"stored":1,"methane":1,"feedback":1,"loop":1,"fragile":1,"slow":1,"recover":1,"indigenous":2,"lifestyle":2,"inuit":2,"hunt":1,"seals":1,"fish":1,"historically":1,"use":1,"skins":1,"sleds":1,"detailed":1,"knowledge":1,"ice":1,"seasons":1,"threats":1,"oil":1,"gas":1,"extraction":2,"pipelines":1,"mining":1,"pollution":1,"conservation":1,"protected":1,"wilderness":1,"strict":1,"limits":1,"cutting":1,"global":1,"emissions":1,"supporting":1,"stewardship":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"freezer":1,"floor":1,"beneath":1,"thawed":1,"rug":1,"water":1,"can":1,"drain":1,"through":1,"surface":1,"stays":1,"soggy":1,"boggy":1,"misconception":1,"nothing":1,"lives":1,"wrong":1,"hosts":1,"foxes":1,"migrating":1,"birds":1,"hardy":1,"corrective":1,"life":1,"sparse":1,"specialised":1,"not":1,"absent":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"how":1,"adapt":1,"their":1,"analyse":2,"evaluate":1,"why":1,"especially":1,"vulnerable":1,"sdg":1}'::jsonb),
