('chunk_660d57597108d16418','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Concept: Depletion (causes and consequences)','**Definition:** Depletion is the reduction of a resource''s stock through consumption until it becomes scarce or exhausted.
**Real-world example:** Groundwater depletion in Punjab (India) and the near-drying of the Aral Sea from over-abstraction for cotton farming.
**Analogy:** Draining a bathtub faster than the tap fills it — soon it''s empty.
**Causes:**
- **Overconsumption** — high per-person use, especially in wealthy nations.
- **Population growth** — more people needing food, water, energy and materials.
- Waste, inefficiency and the throwaway (linear) economy.
**Consequences:**
- **On society:** rising prices, conflict over resources ("water wars"), poverty, migration, unemployment.
- **On environment:** habitat loss, pollution, biodiversity decline, climate change, desertification.
**Why it matters:** Understanding causes lets societies act before resources run out.
**Misconception:** *"Only poor, overpopulated countries cause resource depletion."* Wrong: wealthy nations with smaller populations often have far higher per-capita consumption and ecological footprints. Corrective: depletion is driven by *how much each person consumes* as much as by *how many people* there are.
**IB command-term questions:**
1. (Recall) **Define** resource depletion.
2. (Apply) **Explain** how population growth contributes to depletion.
3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Evaluate** whether overconsumption or population growth is the bigger driver of depletion.

---','{"concept":1,"depletion":8,"causes":3,"and":5,"consequences":2,"definition":1,"the":6,"reduction":1,"resource":3,"stock":1,"through":1,"consumption":2,"until":1,"becomes":1,"scarce":1,"exhausted":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"groundwater":1,"punjab":1,"india":1,"near":1,"drying":1,"aral":1,"sea":1,"from":1,"over":2,"abstraction":1,"for":1,"cotton":1,"farming":1,"analogy":1,"draining":1,"bathtub":1,"faster":1,"than":1,"tap":1,"fills":1,"soon":1,"empty":1,"overconsumption":2,"high":1,"per":2,"person":2,"use":1,"especially":1,"wealthy":2,"nations":2,"population":3,"growth":3,"more":1,"people":2,"needing":1,"food":1,"water":2,"energy":1,"materials":1,"waste":1,"inefficiency":1,"throwaway":1,"linear":1,"economy":1,"society":1,"rising":1,"prices":1,"conflict":1,"resources":2,"wars":1,"poverty":1,"migration":1,"unemployment":1,"environment":1,"habitat":1,"loss":1,"pollution":1,"biodiversity":1,"decline":1,"climate":1,"change":1,"desertification":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"understanding":1,"lets":1,"societies":1,"act":1,"before":1,"run":1,"out":1,"misconception":1,"only":1,"poor":1,"overpopulated":1,"countries":1,"cause":1,"wrong":1,"with":1,"smaller":1,"populations":1,"often":1,"have":1,"far":1,"higher":1,"capita":1,"ecological":1,"footprints":1,"corrective":1,"driven":1,"how":3,"much":2,"each":1,"consumes":1,"many":1,"there":1,"are":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"contributes":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":2,"whether":1,"bigger":1,"driver":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_955e8b2f1fee7b6bc7','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Concept: Conservation','**Definition:** The careful management and protection of resources to prevent waste and depletion so they last for the future.
**Real-world example:** Germany''s recycling system (Green Dot) recovers a large share of packaging waste.
**Analogy:** Conservation is like budgeting pocket money so it lasts the whole month instead of the first day.
**Strategies — the 3 Rs:** **Reduce** (use less), **Reuse** (use again), **Recycle** (make into new products). Also **energy efficiency** (LED lighting, insulation, efficient appliances) and **alternative/renewable energy** (solar, wind, hydro).
**Why it matters:** Conservation slows depletion, cuts pollution and saves money.','{"concept":1,"conservation":3,"definition":1,"the":5,"careful":1,"management":1,"and":4,"protection":1,"resources":1,"prevent":1,"waste":2,"depletion":2,"they":1,"last":1,"for":1,"future":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"germany":1,"recycling":1,"system":1,"green":1,"dot":1,"recovers":1,"large":1,"share":1,"packaging":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"budgeting":1,"pocket":1,"money":2,"lasts":1,"whole":1,"month":1,"instead":1,"first":1,"day":1,"strategies":1,"reduce":1,"use":2,"less":1,"reuse":1,"again":1,"recycle":1,"make":1,"into":1,"new":1,"products":1,"also":1,"energy":2,"efficiency":1,"led":1,"lighting":1,"insulation":1,"efficient":1,"appliances":1,"alternative":1,"renewable":1,"solar":1,"wind":1,"hydro":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"slows":1,"cuts":1,"pollution":1,"saves":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_63f95ec464f4e2053f','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Concept: Linear vs Circular Economy','**Definition:** A **linear economy** follows "take → make → use → dispose." A **circular economy** keeps resources in use as long as possible by reusing, repairing, remanufacturing and recycling — designing out waste.
| | Linear economy | Circular economy |
|---|---------------|------------------|
| Model | Take–make–dispose | Reduce–reuse–recycle–regenerate |
| Waste | High | Minimised (waste = new input) |
| Resource use | One-way, wasteful | Looped, efficient |
| Sustainability | Low | High |
**Benefits of circular economy:** Less waste and pollution, resource security, new "green" jobs, lower emissions, cost savings.
**Case study (circular economy):** The **Netherlands** aims to be fully circular by 2050; the **Ellen MacArthur Foundation** promotes circular design; **Patagonia''s** "Worn Wear" repairs and resells clothing so garments loop back into use instead of landfill.
**Analogy:** Linear economy is a one-use paper plate; circular economy is a washable plate used again and again.
**Misconception:** *"Recycling alone makes an economy circular."* Wrong: recycling is only one loop and still uses energy; true circularity prioritises reducing and reusing first. Corrective: recycling is the last resort *after* reduce and reuse.
**IB command-term questions:**
1. (Recall) **State** the three Rs of conservation.
2. (Apply) **Compare** a linear and a circular economy.
3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Evaluate** how a circular economy supports sustainable development.','{"2050":1,"concept":1,"linear":5,"circular":11,"economy":12,"definition":1,"follows":1,"take":2,"make":2,"use":5,"dispose":2,"keeps":1,"resources":1,"long":1,"possible":1,"reusing":2,"repairing":1,"remanufacturing":1,"and":8,"recycling":4,"designing":1,"out":1,"waste":4,"model":1,"reduce":2,"reuse":2,"recycle":1,"regenerate":1,"high":2,"minimised":1,"new":2,"input":1,"resource":2,"one":3,"way":1,"wasteful":1,"looped":1,"efficient":1,"sustainability":1,"low":1,"benefits":1,"less":1,"pollution":1,"security":1,"green":1,"jobs":1,"lower":1,"emissions":1,"cost":1,"savings":1,"case":1,"study":1,"the":4,"netherlands":1,"aims":1,"fully":1,"ellen":1,"macarthur":1,"foundation":1,"promotes":1,"design":1,"patagonia":1,"worn":1,"wear":1,"repairs":1,"resells":1,"clothing":1,"garments":1,"loop":2,"back":1,"into":1,"instead":1,"landfill":1,"analogy":1,"paper":1,"plate":2,"washable":1,"used":1,"again":2,"misconception":1,"alone":1,"makes":1,"wrong":1,"only":1,"still":1,"uses":1,"energy":1,"true":1,"circularity":1,"prioritises":1,"reducing":1,"first":1,"corrective":1,"last":1,"resort":1,"after":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"three":1,"conservation":1,"apply":1,"compare":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":2,"how":1,"supports":1,"sustainable":1,"development":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c4563dd2d71cb53536','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Concept: Sustainable Development','**Definition:** Development that meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs (Brundtland, 1987).
**Real-world example:** Costa Rica generates almost all its electricity from renewables while protecting its rainforests and growing ecotourism.
**Analogy:** Living off the interest of a bank account, not the capital — so the balance keeps producing forever.
**Key milestones:**
- **Earth Summit (Rio de Janeiro, 1992)** — a landmark UN conference on environment and development.
- **Agenda 21** — its global action plan for sustainable development in the 21st century.
**Three pillars of sustainability:**
| Pillar | Focus | Example |
|--------|-------|---------|
| Social | People, equity, health, education | Fair access to clean water |
| Economic | Jobs, growth, prosperity | Green industries |
| Environmental | Protecting ecosystems & resources | Cutting emissions, conserving forests |
**Balancing human needs with environmental protection:** Sustainable development seeks a middle path where the economy grows, people''s lives improve, *and* the environment is protected — none sacrificed for the others.
**Why it matters:** It is the guiding framework (and basis of the UN SDGs) for global policy today.
**Misconception:** *"Sustainable development means stopping all growth and development."* Wrong: it means developing *differently* — smarter, cleaner and fairer — not halting progress. Corrective: it balances growth with protection rather than ending growth.
**IB command-term questions:**
1. (Recall) **Define** sustainable development.
2. (Apply) **Describe** the three pillars of sustainability with an example of each.
3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Discuss** the difficulty of balancing economic growth with environmental protection. *(Underpins all SDGs.)*

---','{"1987":1,"1992":1,"concept":1,"sustainable":5,"development":8,"definition":1,"that":1,"meets":1,"the":14,"needs":3,"present":1,"without":1,"compromising":1,"ability":1,"future":1,"generations":1,"meet":1,"their":1,"own":1,"brundtland":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":3,"costa":1,"rica":1,"generates":1,"almost":1,"all":3,"its":3,"electricity":1,"from":1,"renewables":1,"while":1,"protecting":2,"rainforests":1,"and":6,"growing":1,"ecotourism":1,"analogy":1,"living":1,"off":1,"interest":1,"bank":1,"account":1,"not":2,"capital":1,"balance":1,"keeps":1,"producing":1,"forever":1,"key":1,"milestones":1,"earth":1,"summit":1,"rio":1,"janeiro":1,"landmark":1,"conference":1,"environment":2,"agenda":1,"global":2,"action":1,"plan":1,"for":3,"21st":1,"century":1,"three":2,"pillars":2,"sustainability":2,"pillar":1,"focus":1,"social":1,"people":2,"equity":1,"health":1,"education":1,"fair":1,"access":1,"clean":1,"water":1,"economic":2,"jobs":1,"growth":5,"prosperity":1,"green":1,"industries":1,"environmental":3,"ecosystems":1,"resources":1,"cutting":1,"emissions":1,"conserving":1,"forests":1,"balancing":2,"human":1,"with":4,"protection":3,"seeks":1,"middle":1,"path":1,"where":1,"economy":1,"grows":1,"lives":1,"improve":1,"protected":1,"none":1,"sacrificed":1,"others":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"guiding":1,"framework":1,"basis":1,"sdgs":2,"policy":1,"today":1,"misconception":1,"means":2,"stopping":1,"wrong":1,"developing":1,"differently":1,"smarter":1,"cleaner":1,"fairer":1,"halting":1,"progress":1,"corrective":1,"balances":1,"rather":1,"than":1,"ending":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"apply":1,"describe":1,"each":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"discuss":1,"difficulty":1,"underpins":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_64ee248e83c8a49650','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','UNIT 3: Policy and Governance','**Key Concept:** Global interactions
**Related Concepts:** Disparity, Power, Cooperation, Sustainability
**Global Context:** *Fairness and development* (rights and responsibilities; the relationship between resources, governance and inequality worldwide).
**Statement of Inquiry:** *Because development is uneven, cooperation between governments and international bodies is needed to manage resources fairly and reduce global disparities.*

**Inquiry Questions**
- **Factual:** How is development measured and where does the North–South divide lie?
- **Conceptual:** How do physical and human factors interact to cause uneven development?
- **Debatable:** Does international aid do more harm than good?

---','{"unit":1,"policy":1,"and":8,"governance":2,"key":1,"concept":1,"global":3,"interactions":1,"related":1,"concepts":1,"disparity":1,"power":1,"cooperation":2,"sustainability":1,"context":1,"fairness":1,"development":4,"rights":1,"responsibilities":1,"the":2,"relationship":1,"between":2,"resources":2,"inequality":1,"worldwide":1,"statement":1,"inquiry":2,"because":1,"uneven":2,"governments":1,"international":2,"bodies":1,"needed":1,"manage":1,"fairly":1,"reduce":1,"disparities":1,"questions":1,"factual":1,"how":2,"measured":1,"where":1,"does":2,"north":1,"south":1,"divide":1,"lie":1,"conceptual":1,"physical":1,"human":1,"factors":1,"interact":1,"cause":1,"debatable":1,"aid":1,"more":1,"harm":1,"than":1,"good":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_72125ec8d95547dce4','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Concept: Development (growth vs development)','**Definition:** **Development** is the improvement in people''s quality of life — including economic wealth, social wellbeing and cultural opportunity. **Growth** is only the increase in the *size* of the economy (more output/income).
**Real-world example:** A country''s GDP may grow from an oil boom (growth), but if hospitals, schools and equality don''t improve, real development hasn''t happened.
**Analogy:** Growth is a plant getting taller; development is the plant getting healthier — stronger roots, fruit and flowers, not just height.
**Aspects of development:**
- **Economic** — income, jobs, industry, infrastructure.
- **Social** — health, education, life expectancy, clean water.
- **Cultural** — freedom, rights, arts, identity, participation.
**Why it matters:** Governments aim for development, not just growth, to genuinely improve lives.
**Misconception:** *"A rich country is automatically a developed country."* Wrong: wealth can be unequally shared; a country can be rich yet have poor health, education or rights. Corrective: development is about wellbeing for all, not just total money.
**IB command-term questions:**
1. (Recall) **Distinguish** between growth and development.
2. (Apply) **Describe** the economic, social and cultural aspects of development.
3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Evaluate** whether economic growth always leads to development.

---','{"concept":1,"development":11,"growth":7,"definition":1,"the":6,"improvement":1,"people":1,"quality":1,"life":2,"including":1,"economic":4,"wealth":2,"social":3,"wellbeing":2,"and":5,"cultural":3,"opportunity":1,"only":1,"increase":1,"size":1,"economy":1,"more":1,"output":1,"income":2,"real":2,"world":1,"example":1,"country":4,"gdp":1,"may":1,"grow":1,"from":1,"oil":1,"boom":1,"but":1,"hospitals":1,"schools":1,"equality":1,"don":1,"improve":2,"hasn":1,"happened":1,"analogy":1,"plant":2,"getting":2,"taller":1,"healthier":1,"stronger":1,"roots":1,"fruit":1,"flowers":1,"not":3,"just":3,"height":1,"aspects":2,"jobs":1,"industry":1,"infrastructure":1,"health":2,"education":2,"expectancy":1,"clean":1,"water":1,"freedom":1,"rights":2,"arts":1,"identity":1,"participation":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"governments":1,"aim":1,"for":2,"genuinely":1,"lives":1,"misconception":1,"rich":2,"automatically":1,"developed":1,"wrong":1,"can":2,"unequally":1,"shared":1,"yet":1,"have":1,"poor":1,"corrective":1,"about":1,"all":1,"total":1,"money":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"distinguish":1,"between":1,"apply":1,"describe":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":2,"whether":1,"always":1,"leads":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_7a63e14e59cd5c4389','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Concept: Physical Factors','**Definition:** Natural conditions of a place that help or hinder development.
- **Climate** — extreme climates (deserts, tropics with disease) can hinder farming and health; temperate climates often help.
- **Natural resources** — oil, minerals, fertile soil and water can boost development (e.g. oil wealth in the Gulf states).
**Analogy:** Physical factors are the "hand of cards" a country is dealt by nature.','{"concept":1,"physical":2,"factors":2,"definition":1,"natural":2,"conditions":1,"place":1,"that":1,"help":2,"hinder":2,"development":2,"climate":1,"extreme":1,"climates":2,"deserts":1,"tropics":1,"with":1,"disease":1,"can":2,"farming":1,"and":2,"health":1,"temperate":1,"often":1,"resources":1,"oil":2,"minerals":1,"fertile":1,"soil":1,"water":1,"boost":1,"wealth":1,"the":2,"gulf":1,"states":1,"analogy":1,"are":1,"hand":1,"cards":1,"country":1,"dealt":1,"nature":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_69ad409591e6bc201a','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Concept: Human-made Factors','**Definition:** Human and economic conditions that shape development.
- **Population** — size, growth rate and structure. A very **high population** growth can strain jobs, food and services; too **low/ageing** a population can shrink the workforce. A balanced, educated population aids development.
- **Education** — a skilled workforce raises productivity and innovation.
- **Jobs** — stable employment reduces poverty and boosts income.
- **Trade** — **exports** (goods sold abroad), **imports** (goods bought in), and the **balance of trade** (exports minus imports). A trade surplus (exports > imports) brings in money; a deficit can create debt.
**How factors interact:** Factors combine and reinforce each other — e.g. a good climate → productive farming → income → schools → educated workers → industry → trade. A weakness in one (e.g. conflict or drought) can undermine the whole chain.
**Why it matters:** Development is never caused by one factor alone; understanding interaction guides better policy.
**Misconception:** *"Countries with lots of natural resources are always developed."* Wrong — the "resource curse": some resource-rich countries suffer conflict, corruption and inequality (e.g. DR Congo''s minerals). Corrective: resources help only when governance, education and fair trade turn them into wellbeing.
**IB command-term questions:**
1. (Recall) **Identify** two physical and two human factors affecting development.
2. (Apply) **Explain** how the balance of trade can affect a country''s development.
3. (Analyse/Evaluate) **Analyse** how physical and human factors interact to influence development.

---','{"concept":1,"human":4,"made":1,"factors":5,"definition":1,"and":11,"economic":1,"conditions":1,"that":1,"shape":1,"development":6,"population":4,"size":1,"growth":2,"rate":1,"structure":1,"very":1,"high":1,"can":5,"strain":1,"jobs":2,"food":1,"services":1,"too":1,"low":1,"ageing":1,"shrink":1,"the":5,"workforce":2,"balanced":1,"educated":2,"aids":1,"education":2,"skilled":1,"raises":1,"productivity":1,"innovation":1,"stable":1,"employment":1,"reduces":1,"poverty":1,"boosts":1,"income":2,"trade":6,"exports":3,"goods":2,"sold":1,"abroad":1,"imports":3,"bought":1,"balance":2,"minus":1,"surplus":1,"brings":1,"money":1,"deficit":1,"create":1,"debt":1,"how":3,"interact":2,"combine":1,"reinforce":1,"each":1,"other":1,"good":1,"climate":1,"productive":1,"farming":1,"schools":1,"workers":1,"industry":1,"weakness":1,"one":2,"conflict":2,"drought":1,"undermine":1,"whole":1,"chain":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"never":1,"caused":1,"factor":1,"alone":1,"understanding":1,"interaction":1,"guides":1,"better":1,"policy":1,"misconception":1,"countries":2,"with":1,"lots":1,"natural":1,"resources":2,"are":1,"always":1,"developed":1,"wrong":1,"resource":2,"curse":1,"some":1,"rich":1,"suffer":1,"corruption":1,"inequality":1,"congo":1,"minerals":1,"corrective":1,"help":1,"only":1,"when":1,"governance":1,"fair":1,"turn":1,"them":1,"into":1,"wellbeing":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"identify":1,"two":2,"physical":2,"affecting":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"affect":1,"country":1,"analyse":2,"evaluate":1,"influence":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_5d9827de83e7866fd4','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Concept: Development Indicators','**Definition:** Statistics used to compare the level of development between places.','{"concept":1,"development":2,"indicators":1,"definition":1,"statistics":1,"used":1,"compare":1,"the":1,"level":1,"between":1,"places":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_527e17919fca0c4dff','file_162fce15bbe62004d5','geography.md','Development Indicators Table','| Indicator | Full name | What it measures | Limitation |
|-----------|-----------|------------------|-----------|
| **GDP (per capita)** | Gross Domestic Product | Total value of goods & services ÷ population | Ignores inequality, informal economy, wellbeing |
| **HDI** | Human Development Index | Combines income, life expectancy & education (0–1) | Doesn''t measure freedom, environment or inequality |
| **Birth/death rate, life expectancy, literacy** | — | Social wellbeing | Single measures give a partial picture |

**Real-world example:** Norway has a very high HDI (~0.96); Niger has a low HDI (~0.4).
**Analogy:** Using one indicator is like judging a student on one test; HDI is like a report card combining several subjects.','{"development":2,"indicators":1,"table":1,"indicator":2,"full":1,"name":1,"what":1,"measures":2,"limitation":1,"gdp":1,"per":1,"capita":1,"gross":1,"domestic":1,"product":1,"total":1,"value":1,"goods":1,"services":1,"population":1,"ignores":1,"inequality":2,"informal":1,"economy":1,"wellbeing":2,"hdi":4,"human":1,"index":1,"combines":1,"income":1,"life":2,"expectancy":2,"education":1,"doesn":1,"measure":1,"freedom":1,"environment":1,"birth":1,"death":1,"rate":1,"literacy":1,"social":1,"single":1,"give":1,"partial":1,"picture":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"norway":1,"has":2,"very":1,"high":1,"niger":1,"low":1,"analogy":1,"using":1,"one":2,"like":2,"judging":1,"student":1,"test":1,"report":1,"card":1,"combining":1,"several":1,"subjects":1}'::jsonb);